<doc id="1186896" wikidata="Q4748472" url="?curid=1186896" title="Ample line bundle">
<text>In mathematics, a distinctive feature of algebraic geometry is that some line bundles on a projective variety can be considered &quot;positive&quot;, while others are &quot;negative&quot; (or a mixture of the two). The most important notion of positivity is that of an ample line bundle, although there are several related classes of line bundles. Roughly speaking, positivity properties of a line bundle are related to having many global sections. Understanding the ample line bundles on a given variety formula_1 amounts to understanding the different ways of mapping formula_1 into projective spaces. In view of the correspondence between line bundles and divisors (built from codimension-1 subvarieties), there is an equivalent notion of an ample divisor.

In more detail, a line bundle is called basepoint-free if it has enough sections to give a morphism to projective space. A line bundle is semi-ample if some positive power of it is basepoint-free; semi-ampleness is a kind of &quot;nonnegativity&quot;. More strongly, a line bundle on a complete variety formula_1 is very ample if it has enough sections to give a closed immersion (or &quot;embedding&quot;) of formula_1 into a projective space. A line bundle is ample if some positive power is very ample.

An ample line bundle on a projective variety formula_1 has positive degree on every curve in formula_1. The converse is not quite true, but there are corrected versions of the converse, the Nakai–Moishezon and Kleiman criteria for ampleness.

==Introduction==
===Pullback of a line bundle and hyperplane divisors===
Given a morphism formula_7 of schemes, a vector bundle formula_8 (or more generally a coherent sheaf on formula_9) has a pullback to formula_1, formula_11 where the projection formula_12 is the projection on the first coordinate (see Sheaf of modules#Operations). The pullback of a vector bundle is a vector bundle of the same rank. In particular, the pullback of a line bundle is a line bundle. (Briefly, the fiber of formula_13 at a point formula_14 is the fiber of formula_15 at formula_16.)

The notions described in this article are related to this construction in the case of a morphism to projective space
:formula_17
with formula_18 the line bundle on projective space whose global sections are the homogeneous polynomials of degree 1 (that is, linear functions) in variables formula_19. The line bundle formula_20 can also be described as the line bundle associated to a hyperplane in formula_21 (because the zero set of a section of formula_20 is a hyperplane). If formula_23 is a closed immersion, for example, it follows that the pullback formula_24 is the line bundle on formula_1 associated to a hyperplane section (the intersection of formula_1 with a hyperplane in formula_27).

===Basepoint-free line bundles===
Let formula_1 be a scheme over a field formula_29 (for example, an algebraic variety) with a line bundle formula_30. (A line bundle may also be called an invertible sheaf.) Let formula_31 be elements of the formula_29-vector space formula_33 of global sections of formula_30. The zero set of each section is a closed subset of formula_1; let formula_36 be the open subset of points at which at least one of formula_37 is not zero. Then these sections define a morphism
:formula_38

In more detail: for each point formula_39 of formula_36, the fiber of formula_30 over formula_39 is a 1-dimensional vector space over the residue field formula_43. Choosing a basis for this fiber makes formula_44 into a sequence of formula_45 numbers, not all zero, and hence a point in projective space. Changing the choice of basis scales all the numbers by the same nonzero constant, and so the point in projective space is independent of the choice.

Moreover, this morphism has the property that the restriction of formula_30 to formula_36 is isomorphic to the pullback formula_48.

The base locus of a line bundle formula_30 on a scheme formula_1 is the intersection of the zero sets of all global sections of formula_30. A line bundle formula_30 is called basepoint-free if its base locus is empty. That is, for every point formula_39 of formula_1 there is a global section of formula_30 which is nonzero at formula_39. If formula_1 is proper over a field formula_29, then the vector space formula_33 of global sections has finite dimension; the dimension is called formula_60. So a basepoint-free line bundle formula_30 determines a morphism formula_62 over formula_29, where formula_64, given by choosing a basis for formula_33. Without making a choice, this can be described as the morphism
:formula_66
from formula_1 to the space of hyperplanes in formula_33, canonically associated to the basepoint-free line bundle formula_30. This morphism has the property that formula_30 is the pullback formula_48.

Conversely, for any morphism formula_23 from a scheme formula_1 to a projective space formula_27 over formula_29, the pullback line bundle formula_48 is basepoint-free. Indeed, formula_20 is basepoint-free on formula_27, because for every point formula_79 in formula_27 there is a hyperplane not containing formula_79. Therefore, for every point formula_39 in formula_1, there is a section formula_84 of formula_20 over formula_27 that is not zero at formula_87, and the pullback of formula_84 is a global section of formula_48 that is not zero at formula_39. In short, basepoint-free line bundles are exactly those that can be expressed as the pullback of formula_20 by some morphism to a projective space.

===Nef, globally generated, semi-ample===
The degree of a line bundle &quot;L&quot; on a proper curve &quot;C&quot; over &quot;k&quot; is defined as the degree of the divisor (&quot;s&quot;) of any nonzero rational section &quot;s&quot; of &quot;L&quot;. The coefficients of this divisor are positive at points where &quot;s&quot; vanishes and negative where &quot;s&quot; has a pole. Therefore, any line bundle &quot;L&quot; on a curve &quot;C&quot; such that formula_92 has nonnegative degree (because sections of &quot;L&quot; over &quot;C&quot;, as opposed to rational sections, have no poles). In particular, every basepoint-free line bundle on a curve has nonnegative degree. As a result, a basepoint-free line bundle &quot;L&quot; on any proper scheme &quot;X&quot; over a field is nef, meaning that &quot;L&quot; has nonnegative degree on every (irreducible) curve in &quot;X&quot;.

More generally, a sheaf &quot;F&quot; of formula_93-modules on a scheme &quot;X&quot; is said to be globally generated if there is a set &quot;I&quot; of global sections formula_94 such that the corresponding morphism
:formula_95
of sheaves is surjective. A line bundle is globally generated if and only if it is basepoint-free.

For example, every quasi-coherent sheaf on an affine scheme is globally generated. Analogously, in complex geometry, Cartan&#x27;s theorem A says that every coherent sheaf on a Stein manifold is globally generated.

A line bundle &quot;L&quot; on a proper scheme over a field is semi-ample if there is a positive integer &quot;r&quot; such that the tensor power formula_96 is basepoint-free. A semi-ample line bundle is nef (by the corresponding fact for basepoint-free line bundles).

===Very ample line bundles===
A line bundle formula_30 on a proper scheme formula_1 over a field formula_29 is said to be very ample if it is basepoint-free and the associated morphism
:formula_100
is an immersion. Here formula_64. Equivalently, formula_30 is very ample if formula_1 can be embedded into a projective space of some dimension over formula_29 in such a way that formula_30 is the restriction of the line bundle formula_20 to formula_1. The latter definition is used to define very ampleness for a line bundle on a proper scheme over any commutative ring.

The name &quot;very ample&quot; was introduced by Alexander Grothendieck in 1961. Various names had been used earlier in the context of linear systems of divisors.

For a very ample line bundle formula_30 on a proper scheme formula_1 over a field with associated morphism formula_23, the degree of formula_30 on a curve formula_112 in formula_1 is the degree of formula_114 as a curve in formula_27. So formula_30 has positive degree on every curve in formula_1 (because every subvariety of projective space has positive degree).

== Definitions ==

=== Ample invertible sheaves on quasi-compact schemes ===
Ample line bundles are used most often on proper schemes, but they can be defined in much wider generality.

Let &quot;X&quot; be a scheme, and let formula_118 be an invertible sheaf on &quot;X&quot;. For each formula_119, let formula_120 denote the ideal sheaf of the reduced subscheme supported only at &quot;x&quot;. For formula_121, define
formula_122
Equivalently, if formula_123 denotes the residue field at &quot;x&quot; (considered as a skyscraper sheaf supported at &quot;x&quot;), then
formula_124
where formula_125 is the image of &quot;s&quot; in the tensor product.

Fix formula_121. For every &quot;s&quot;, the restriction formula_127 is a free formula_128-module trivialized by the restriction of &quot;s&quot;, meaning the multiplication-by-s morphism formula_129 is an isomorphism. The set formula_130 is always open, and the inclusion morphism formula_131 is an affine morphism. Despite this, formula_130 need not be an affine scheme. For example, if formula_133, then formula_134 is open in itself and affine over itself but generally not affine.

Assume &quot;X&quot; is quasi-compact. Then formula_118 is ample if, for every formula_119, there exists an formula_137 and an formula_138 such that formula_139 and formula_130 is an affine scheme. For example, the trivial line bundle formula_128 is ample if and only if &quot;X&quot; is quasi-affine.

In general, it is not true that every formula_130 is affine. For example, if formula_143 for some point &quot;O&quot;, and if formula_118 is the restriction of formula_145 to &quot;X&quot;, then formula_118 and formula_145 have the same global sections, and the non-vanishing locus of a section of formula_118 is affine if and only if the corresponding section of formula_145 contains &quot;O&quot;.

It is necessary to allow powers of formula_118 in the definition. In fact, for every &quot;N&quot;, it is possible that formula_130 is non-affine for every formula_138 with formula_153. Indeed, suppose &quot;Z&quot; is a finite set of points in formula_154, formula_155, and formula_156. The vanishing loci of the sections of formula_157 are plane curves of degree &quot;N&quot;. By taking &quot;Z&quot; to be a sufficiently large set of points in general position, we may ensure that no plane curve of degree &quot;N&quot; (and hence any lower degree) contains all the points of &quot;Z&quot;. In particular their non-vanishing loci are all non-affine.

Define formula_158. Let formula_159 denote the structural morphism. There is a natural isomorphism between formula_128-algebra homomorphisms formula_161 and endomorphisms of the graded ring &quot;S&quot;. The identity endomorphism of &quot;S&quot; corresponds to a homomorphism formula_162. Applying the formula_163 functor produces a morphism from an open subscheme of &quot;X&quot;, denoted formula_164, to formula_165.

The basic characterization of ample invertible sheaves states that if &quot;X&quot; is a quasi-compact quasi-separated scheme and formula_118 is an invertible sheaf on &quot;X&quot;, then the following assertions are equivalent:
# formula_118 is ample.
# The open sets formula_130, where formula_138 and formula_170, form a basis for the topology of &quot;X&quot;.
# The open sets formula_130 with the property of being affine, where formula_138 and formula_170, form a basis for the topology of &quot;X&quot;.
# formula_174 and the morphism formula_175 is a dominant open immersion.
# formula_174 and the morphism formula_175 is a homeomorphism of the underlying topological space of &quot;X&quot; with its image.
# For every quasi-coherent sheaf formula_178 on &quot;X&quot;, the canonical map formula_179 is surjective.
# For every quasi-coherent sheaf of ideals formula_180 on &quot;X&quot;, the canonical map formula_181 is surjective.
# For every quasi-coherent sheaf of ideals formula_180 on &quot;X&quot;, the canonical map formula_181 is surjective.
# For every quasi-coherent sheaf formula_178 of finite type on &quot;X&quot;, there exists an integer formula_185 such that for formula_186, formula_187 is generated by its global sections.
# For every quasi-coherent sheaf formula_178 of finite type on &quot;X&quot;, there exists integers formula_189 and formula_190 such that formula_178 is isomorphic to a quotient of formula_192.
# For every quasi-coherent sheaf of ideals formula_180 of finite type on &quot;X&quot;, there exists integers formula_189 and formula_190 such that formula_180 is isomorphic to a quotient of formula_192.

=== On proper schemes ===
When &quot;X&quot; is separated and finite type over an affine scheme, an invertible sheaf formula_118 is ample if and only if there exists a positive integer &quot;r&quot; such that the tensor power formula_199 is very ample. In particular, a proper scheme over &quot;R&quot; has an ample line bundle if and only if it is projective over &quot;R&quot;. Often, this characterization is taken as the definition of ampleness.

The rest of this article will concentrate on ampleness on proper schemes over a field, as this is the most important case. An ample line bundle on a proper scheme &quot;X&quot; over a field has positive degree on every curve in &quot;X&quot;, by the corresponding statement for very ample line bundles.

A Cartier divisor &quot;D&quot; on a proper scheme &quot;X&quot; over a field &quot;k&quot; is said to be ample if the corresponding line bundle &quot;O&quot;(&quot;D&quot;) is ample. (For example, if &quot;X&quot; is smooth over &quot;k&quot;, then a Cartier divisor can be identified with a finite linear combination of closed codimension-1 subvarieties of &quot;X&quot; with integer coefficients.)

Weakening the notion of &quot;very ample&quot; to &quot;ample&quot; gives a flexible concept with a wide variety of different characterizations. A first point is that tensoring high powers of an ample line bundle with any coherent sheaf whatsoever gives a sheaf with many global sections. More precisely, a line bundle &quot;L&quot; on a proper scheme &quot;X&quot; over a field (or more generally over a Noetherian ring) is ample if and only if for every coherent sheaf &quot;F&quot; on &quot;X&quot;, there is an integer &quot;s&quot; such that the sheaf formula_200 is globally generated for all formula_201. Here &quot;s&quot; may depend on &quot;F&quot;.

Another characterization of ampleness, known as the Cartan–Serre–Grothendieck theorem, is in terms of coherent sheaf cohomology. Namely, a line bundle &quot;L&quot; on a proper scheme &quot;X&quot; over a field (or more generally over a Noetherian ring) is ample if and only if for every coherent sheaf &quot;F&quot; on &quot;X&quot;, there is an integer &quot;s&quot; such that
:formula_202
for all formula_203 and all formula_201. In particular, high powers of an ample line bundle kill cohomology in positive degrees. This implication is called the Serre vanishing theorem, proved by Jean-Pierre Serre in his 1955 paper Faisceaux algébriques cohérents.

==Examples/Non-examples==
* The trivial line bundle formula_93 on a projective variety &quot;X&quot; of positive dimension is basepoint-free but not ample. More generally, for any morphism &quot;f&quot; from a projective variety &quot;X&quot; to some projective space formula_27 over a field, the pullback line bundle formula_207 is always basepoint-free, whereas &quot;L&quot; is ample if and only if the morphism &quot;f&quot; is finite (that is, all fibers of &quot;f&quot; have dimension 0 or are empty).
* For an integer &quot;d&quot;, the space of sections of the line bundle &quot;O&quot;(&quot;d&quot;) over formula_208 is the complex vector space of homogeneous polynomials of degree &quot;d&quot; in variables &quot;x&quot;,&quot;y&quot;. In particular, this space is zero for &quot;d&quot; &lt; 0. For formula_209, the morphism to projective space given by &quot;O&quot;(&quot;d&quot;) is
::formula_210
:by
::formula_211
:This is a closed immersion for formula_212, with image a rational normal curve of degree &quot;d&quot; in formula_213. Therefore, &quot;O&quot;(&quot;d&quot;) is basepoint-free if and only if formula_209, and very ample if and only if formula_212. It follows that &quot;O&quot;(&quot;d&quot;) is ample if and only if formula_212.
* For an example where &quot;ample&quot; and &quot;very ample&quot; are different, let &quot;X&quot; be a smooth projective curve of genus 1 (an elliptic curve) over C, and let &quot;p&quot; be a complex point of &quot;X&quot;. Let &quot;O&quot;(&quot;p&quot;) be the associated line bundle of degree 1 on &quot;X&quot;. Then the complex vector space of global sections of &quot;O&quot;(&quot;p&quot;) has dimension 1, spanned by a section that vanishes at &quot;p&quot;. So the base locus of &quot;O&quot;(&quot;p&quot;) is equal to &quot;p&quot;. On the other hand, &quot;O&quot;(2&quot;p&quot;) is basepoint-free, and &quot;O&quot;(&quot;dp&quot;) is very ample for formula_217 (giving an embedding of &quot;X&quot; as an elliptic curve of degree &quot;d&quot; in formula_218). Therefore, &quot;O&quot;(&quot;p&quot;) is ample but not very ample. Also, &quot;O&quot;(2&quot;p&quot;) is ample and basepoint-free but not very ample; the associated morphism to projective space is a ramified double cover formula_219.
* On curves of higher genus, there are ample line bundles &quot;L&quot; for which every global section is zero. (But high multiples of &quot;L&quot; have many sections, by definition.) For example, let &quot;X&quot; be a smooth plane quartic curve (of degree 4 in formula_220) over C, and let &quot;p&quot; and &quot;q&quot; be distinct complex points of &quot;X&quot;. Then the line bundle formula_221 is ample but has formula_222.

==Criteria for ampleness of line bundles==
===Intersection theory===
To determine whether a given line bundle on a projective variety &quot;X&quot; is ample, the following &quot;numerical criteria&quot; (in terms of intersection numbers) are often the most useful. It is equivalent to ask when a Cartier divisor &quot;D&quot; on &quot;X&quot; is ample, meaning that the associated line bundle &quot;O&quot;(&quot;D&quot;) is ample. The intersection number formula_223 can be defined as the degree of the line bundle &quot;O&quot;(&quot;D&quot;) restricted to &quot;C&quot;. In the other direction, for a line bundle &quot;L&quot; on a projective variety, the first Chern class formula_224 means the associated Cartier divisor (defined up to linear equivalence), the divisor of any nonzero rational section of &quot;L&quot;.

On a smooth projective curve &quot;X&quot; over an algebraically closed field &quot;k&quot;, a line bundle &quot;L&quot; is very ample if and only if formula_225 for all &quot;k&quot;-rational points &quot;x&quot;,&quot;y&quot; in &quot;X&quot;. Let &quot;g&quot; be the genus of &quot;X&quot;. By the Riemann–Roch theorem, every line bundle of degree at least 2&quot;g&quot; + 1 satisfies this condition and hence is very ample. As a result, a line bundle on a curve is ample if and only if it has positive degree.

For example, the canonical bundle formula_226 of a curve &quot;X&quot; has degree 2&quot;g&quot; − 2, and so it is ample if and only if formula_227. The curves with ample canonical bundle form an important class; for example, over the complex numbers, these are the curves with a metric of negative curvature. The canonical bundle is very ample if and only if formula_227 and the curve is not hyperelliptic.

The Nakai–Moishezon criterion (named for Yoshikazu Nakai (1963) and Boris Moishezon (1964)) states that a line bundle &quot;L&quot; on a proper scheme &quot;X&quot; over a field is ample if and only if formula_229 for every (irreducible) closed subvariety &quot;Y&quot; of &quot;X&quot; (&quot;Y&quot; is not allowed to be a point). In terms of divisors, a Cartier divisor &quot;D&quot; is ample if and only if formula_230 for every (nonzero-dimensional) subvariety &quot;Y&quot; of &quot;X&quot;. For &quot;X&quot; a curve, this says that a divisor is ample if and only if it has positive degree. For &quot;X&quot; a surface, the criterion says that a divisor &quot;D&quot; is ample if and only if its self-intersection number formula_231 is positive and every curve &quot;C&quot; on &quot;X&quot; has formula_232.

===Kleiman&#x27;s criterion===
To state Kleiman&#x27;s criterion (1966), let &quot;X&quot; be a projective scheme over a field. Let formula_233 be the real vector space of 1-cycles (real linear combinations of curves in &quot;X&quot;) modulo numerical equivalence, meaning that two 1-cycles &quot;A&quot; and &quot;B&quot; are equal in formula_233 if and only if every line bundle has the same degree on &quot;A&quot; and on &quot;B&quot;. By the Néron–Severi theorem, the real vector space formula_233 has finite dimension. Kleiman&#x27;s criterion states that a line bundle &quot;L&quot; on &quot;X&quot; is ample if and only if &quot;L&quot; has positive degree on every nonzero element &quot;C&quot; of the closure of the cone of curves NE(&quot;X&quot;) in formula_233. (This is slightly stronger than saying that &quot;L&quot; has positive degree on every curve.) Equivalently, a line bundle is ample if and only if its class in the dual vector space formula_237 is in the interior of the nef cone.

Kleiman&#x27;s criterion fails in general for proper (rather than projective) schemes &quot;X&quot; over a field, although it holds if &quot;X&quot; is smooth or more generally Q-factorial.

A line bundle on a projective variety is called strictly nef if it has positive degree on every curve. and David Mumford constructed line bundles on smooth projective surfaces that are strictly nef but not ample. This shows that the condition formula_238 cannot be omitted in the Nakai–Moishezon criterion, and it is necessary to use the closure of NE(&quot;X&quot;) rather than NE(&quot;X&quot;) in Kleiman&#x27;s criterion. Every nef line bundle on a surface has formula_239, and Nagata and Mumford&#x27;s examples have formula_240.

C. S. Seshadri showed that a line bundle &quot;L&quot; on a proper scheme over an algebraically closed field is ample if and only if there is a positive real number ε such that deg(&quot;L&quot;|&quot;C&quot;) ≥ ε&quot;m&quot;(&quot;C&quot;) for all (irreducible) curves &quot;C&quot; in &quot;X&quot;, where &quot;m&quot;(&quot;C&quot;) is the maximum of the multiplicities at the points of &quot;C&quot;.

Several characterizations of ampleness hold more generally for line bundles on a proper algebraic space over a field &quot;k&quot;. In particular, the Nakai-Moishezon criterion is valid in that generality. The Cartan-Serre-Grothendieck criterion holds even more generally, for a proper algebraic space over a Noetherian ring &quot;R&quot;. (If a proper algebraic space over &quot;R&quot; has an ample line bundle, then it is in fact a projective scheme over &quot;R&quot;.) Kleiman&#x27;s criterion fails for proper algebraic spaces &quot;X&quot; over a field, even if &quot;X&quot; is smooth.

===Openness of ampleness===
On a projective scheme &quot;X&quot; over a field, Kleiman&#x27;s criterion implies that ampleness is an open condition on the class of an R-divisor (an R-linear combination of Cartier divisors) in formula_237, with its topology based on the topology of the real numbers. (An R-divisor is defined to be ample if it can be written as a positive linear combination of ample Cartier divisors.) An elementary special case is: for an ample divisor &quot;H&quot; and any divisor &quot;E&quot;, there is a positive real number &quot;b&quot; such that formula_242 is ample for all real numbers &quot;a&quot; of absolute value less than &quot;b&quot;. In terms of divisors with integer coefficients (or line bundles), this means that &quot;nH&quot; + &quot;E&quot; is ample for all sufficiently large positive integers &quot;n&quot;.

Ampleness is also an open condition in a quite different sense, when the variety or line bundle is varied in an algebraic family. Namely, let formula_243 be a proper morphism of schemes, and let &quot;L&quot; be a line bundle on &quot;X&quot;. Then the set of points &quot;y&quot; in &quot;Y&quot; such that &quot;L&quot; is ample on the fiber formula_244 is open (in the Zariski topology). More strongly, if &quot;L&quot; is ample on one fiber formula_244, then there is an affine open neighborhood &quot;U&quot; of &quot;y&quot; such that &quot;L&quot; is ample on formula_246 over &quot;U&quot;.

===Kleiman&#x27;s other characterizations of ampleness===
Kleiman also proved the following characterizations of ampleness, which can be viewed as intermediate steps between the definition of ampleness and numerical criteria. Namely, for a line bundle &quot;L&quot; on a proper scheme &quot;X&quot; over a field, the following are equivalent:
* &quot;L&quot; is ample.
* For every (irreducible) subvariety formula_247 of positive dimension, there is a positive integer &quot;r&quot; and a section formula_248 which is not identically zero but vanishes at some point of &quot;Y&quot;.
* For every (irreducible) subvariety formula_247 of positive dimension, the holomorphic Euler characteristics of powers of &quot;L&quot; on &quot;Y&quot; go to infinity:
::formula_250 as formula_251.

==Generalizations==
===Ample vector bundles===
Robin Hartshorne defined a vector bundle &quot;F&quot; on a projective scheme &quot;X&quot; over a field to be ample if the line bundle formula_20 on the space formula_253 of hyperplanes in &quot;F&quot; is ample.

Several properties of ample line bundles extend to ample vector bundles. For example, a vector bundle &quot;F&quot; is ample if and only if high symmetric powers of &quot;F&quot; kill the cohomology formula_254 of coherent sheaves for all formula_203. Also, the Chern class formula_256 of an ample vector bundle has positive degree on every &quot;r&quot;-dimensional subvariety of &quot;X&quot;, for formula_257.

===Big line bundles===

A useful weakening of ampleness, notably in birational geometry, is the notion of a big line bundle. A line bundle &quot;L&quot; on a projective variety &quot;X&quot; of dimension &quot;n&quot; over a field is said to be big if there is a positive real number &quot;a&quot; and a positive integer formula_258 such that formula_259 for all formula_260. This is the maximum possible growth rate for the spaces of sections of powers of &quot;L&quot;, in the sense that for every line bundle &quot;L&quot; on &quot;X&quot; there is a positive number &quot;b&quot; with formula_261 for all &quot;j&quot; &gt; 0.

There are several other characterizations of big line bundles. First, a line bundle is big if and only if there is a positive integer &quot;r&quot; such that the rational map from &quot;X&quot; to formula_262 given by the sections of formula_96 is birational onto its image. Also, a line bundle &quot;L&quot; is big if and only if it has a positive tensor power which is the tensor product of an ample line bundle &quot;A&quot; and an effective line bundle &quot;B&quot; (meaning that formula_264). Finally, a line bundle is big if and only if its class in formula_237 is in the interior of the cone of effective divisors.

Bigness can be viewed as a birationally invariant analog of ampleness. For example, if formula_243 is a dominant rational map between smooth projective varieties of the same dimension, then the pullback of a big line bundle on &quot;Y&quot; is big on &quot;X&quot;. (At first sight, the pullback is only a line bundle on the open subset of &quot;X&quot; where &quot;f&quot; is a morphism, but this extends uniquely to a line bundle on all of &quot;X&quot;.) For ample line bundles, one can only say that the pullback of an ample line bundle by a finite morphism is ample.

Example: Let &quot;X&quot; be the blow-up of the projective plane formula_220 at a point over the complex numbers. Let &quot;H&quot; be the pullback to &quot;X&quot; of a line on formula_220, and let &quot;E&quot; be the exceptional curve of the blow-up formula_269. Then the divisor &quot;H&quot; + &quot;E&quot; is big but not ample (or even nef) on &quot;X&quot;, because
:formula_270

This negativity also implies that the base locus of &quot;H&quot; + &quot;E&quot; (or of any positive multiple) contains the curve &quot;E&quot;. In fact, this base locus is equal to &quot;E&quot;.

== Relative ampleness ==
Given a quasi-compact morphism of schemes formula_271, an invertible sheaf &quot;L&quot; on &quot;X&quot; is said to be ample relative to &quot;f&quot; or &quot;f&quot;-ample if the following equivalent conditions are met:
# For each open affine subset formula_272, the restriction of &quot;L&quot; to formula_246 is ample (in the usual sense).
# &quot;f&quot; is quasi-separated and there is an open immersion formula_274 induced by the adjunction map:
#:formula_275.
# The condition 2. without &quot;open&quot;.

The condition 2 says (roughly) that &quot;X&quot; can be openly compactified to a projective scheme with formula_276 (not just to a proper scheme).

==See also==
===General algebraic geometry===
* Algebraic geometry of projective spaces
* Fano variety: a variety whose canonical bundle is anti-ample
* Matsusaka&#x27;s big theorem
* Divisorial scheme: a scheme admitting an ample family of line bundles

===Ampleness in complex geometry===
* Holomorphic vector bundle
* Kodaira embedding theorem: on a compact complex manifold, ampleness and positivity coincide.
* Kodaira vanishing theorem
* Lefschetz hyperplane theorem: an ample divisor in a complex projective variety &quot;X&quot; is topologically similar to &quot;X&quot;.

